{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}} [[File:Natuurtop 2015 (15833572204).jpg|thumb|Koert van Mensvoort, 2015]] '''Koert van Mensvoort''' (born 9 April 1974) is an artist, philosopher and scientist best known for his work on the philosophical concept of Next Nature.
== Academic == Van Mensvoort is the head of the Next Nature Lab at the Industrial Design Department of the [[Eindhoven University of Technology]], a position he has held since 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tue.nl/en/university/departments/industrial-design/research/experts-expertise/detail/ep/e/d/19981699/?no_cache=1&cHash=d80a19a66b9ea57aa8b5bec535631729 |title=dr.ir. K.M. (Koert) van Mensvoort MFA |publisher=Tue.nl |date=January 19, 2011 |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> In 1997 Van Mensvoort received a Master of Science degree in computer science, specializing in computer graphics from the Eindhoven University of Technology. In 2000 he completed a Master of Fine Arts degree at the Sandberg Institute in [[Amsterdam]]. In 2008 he was Visionary in Residence at [[Art Center College of Design]] in Pasadena. Van Mensvoort received a doctorate from the Eindhoven University of Technology in 2009 for his thesis ''What You See Is What You Feel''.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/What-You-See-Feel-simulation/dp/3838325516/ref=cm_cr_pr_product_top |title=What You See Is What You Feel: On the simulation of touch in graphical user interfaces (9783838325514): Koert Van Mensvoort: Books |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/02/arts/arts-online-innovative-webmasters-chase-fame-at-browserday.html?pagewanted=print&src=pm | work=The New York Times | first=Matthew | last=Mirapaul | title=ARTS ONLINE; Innovative Webmasters Chase Fame at Browserday | date=April 2, 2001}}</ref> Van Mensvoort is the founder and director of the Next Nature Network, a design-and-think tank based in Amsterdam, The Netherlands.
== Projects == Van Mensvoort works in many different media to materialize his philosophy. Most of his multi-media projects are concerned with how technology becomes so omnipresent, intricate and uncontrollable we start to perceive it as a nature of its own. Notable projects
* The book ''Next Nature: Nature Changes Along With Us''<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Next-Nature-Changes-Along-Us/dp/8492861533/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1328464267&sr=8-1 |title=Next Nature: Nature Changes Along with Us: Amazon.co.uk: Bruce Sterling, Kelly Kevin, Peter Lunenfeld, Koert Van Mensvoort: 9788492861538: Books |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |date= |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> with [[Hendrik-Jan Grievink]]. [[Scientific American]] magazine wrote in a review that “next nature can give us a new vocabulary and a new philosophy to see and design the world.”<ref>{{cite web|last=Agapakis |first=Christina |url=http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/oscillator/2011/12/29/nurturing-next-nature/ |title=Nurturing Next Nature &#124; Oscillator, Scientific American Blog Network |publisher=Blogs.scientificamerican.com |date=December 29, 2011 |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> * The Rise and Fall of Rayfish Footwear<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rayfish.com |title=The Rise and Fall of Rayfish Footwear|publisher=Nextnature.net |date= |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref> online film project on the fictional company Rayfish.com<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rayfish.com|title=RayFish Footwear – Grow your own sneaker|work=rayfish.com}}</ref> that offered personalized sneakers crafted from genetically modified stingray leather. * The NANO Supermarket<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nos.nl/video/193750-nanotechnologie-rukt-op.html |title=NOS Nieuws – Nanotechnologie rukt op |publisher=Nos.nl |date= |accessdate=February 7, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115141105/http://nos.nl/video/193750-nanotechnologie-rukt-op.html |archivedate=January 15, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Nextnature.net |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y4sCfTh9Ig4 |title=TEDxBrainport – Koert Van Mensvoort – Nano Supermarket |publisher=YouTube |date=May 13, 2011 |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> a mobile exhibition featuring nanotech products that might be on the market within the next ten years. * The Datafountain,<ref>{{cite web|author=nextnature |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ISr6LYjbFyM |title=Datafountain – Money translated to Water |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2004/09/06/the-datafountain-the-real-time-global-currency-fountain/ |title=The Datafountain: the real-time global currency fountain |publisher=Engadget |date= |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> is an internet-enabled water fountain connected to money currency rates. * The documentary ''Daddy! The Woods Smell of Shampoo'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vpro.nl/programma/bonanza/afleveringen/3529683/ |title=Bonanza -> Afleveringen -> HET BOS RUIKT NAAR SHAMPOO |publisher=Vpro.nl |date=April 24, 2001 |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> exploring the intimate role media play in our society: how the media have become fundamentally part of the cycle through which we create meaning and it effectively becomes impossible to distinguish media from reality. * The Fake for Real memory game<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fakeforreal.com |title=Fake For Real memory game (online version) |publisher=BIS |date=Oct 20, 2007 |accessdate=March 7, 2012}}</ref> on the tension between reality and simulation. * The online interactive dance film ''Drift'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://download.omroep.nl/nps/dekortefilm/mixedup/drift/index.html |title=Drift |publisher=NPS |date=Sep 20, 2002 |accessdate=March 7, 2012}}</ref> featuring a dancer without a body but kinetic points in space, dance and choreography by [[Nancy Mauro-Flude]]. * The Biggest Visual Power Show, a pop conference held in Amsterdam, Zollverein and Los Angeles.
== Books == Van Mensvoort has co-authored numerous books and publications. * ''Next Nature: Nature Changes Along With Us'',<ref name="auto1" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archief.nrc.nl/index.php/2011/November/25/Boeken/b01/Techtuur+heeft+de+toekomst/check=Y |title=Techtuur heeft de toekomst |publisher=Archief.nrc.nl |date=November 25, 2011 |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> edited and designed by Koert van Mensvoort and [[Hendrik-Jan Grievink]]. The book examines people’s notion of nature and how the image of nature as static, balanced and harmonic is naive and up for reconsideration. Where technology and nature are traditionally seen as opposed, they now appear to merge or even trade places. * ''Visual Power'' * ''What You See Is What You Feel''<ref name="auto" /> * ''Natuur 2.0'' * ''Entry Paradise – New Worlds of Design'' * ''Artvertising'' * ''Style First''
