{{Infobox religious biography |background = #FFD068 |name = Soyu Matsuoka |image= Soyu_Matsuoka_photograph.jpg |caption = |alias = |dharma name = |birth_date = 1912 |birth_place = [[Hiroshima, Japan]] |death_date = 1997 |death_place = |nationality = |religion = [[Zen Buddhism]] |school = [[Sōtō]] |lineage = |title = |location = |education = [[Komazawa University]] |teacher = |reincarnation of = |predecessor = |successor = Richard Langlois, Zenkai Taiun Michael Elliston (East Coast), Hogaku Shozen McGuire (West Coast) |students = |spouse = |children = |website = http://www.azszc.org/dedication.htm }} {{Zen Buddhism}} {{Western Buddhism}} Dr. '''Soyu Matsuoka''' ('''松岡 操雄''', 1912–1997), along with [[Sokei-an]] and [[Nyogen Senzaki]], was one of the early [[Zen]] teachers to make the [[United States]] his home.
==Biography== Shortly before World War II Matsuoka came to the USA, to serve Japanese immigrants.{{sfn|Ford|2006|p=80–81}} He came to be the assistant to the abbott of Zenshuji Temple in Los Angeles, and was later the supervisor at Sokoji Soto Zen Mission (Temple) in San Francisco.
Matsuoka established the Chicago Buddhist Temple in 1949 (now the Zen Buddhist Temple of Chicago). In the 1960s he gathered a following of [[United States|Americans]]. Richard Langlois was one of the first Americans ever to receive [[Dharma transmission]]. In 1970 Matsuoka left Chicago and moved to [[Long Beach, California]], where he continued to preside over other communities. Matsuoka left the Soto-shu,{{sfn|Ford|2006|p=80–81}} Matsuoka holding that Zen is a personal experience, and that the authority of the Soto Sect and its training monasteries (専門僧堂) inhibit the practice of Zen.
Matsuoka died in 1997.{{sfn|Ford|2006|p=80–81}}{{sfn|Prebish|1999|p=13}}{{sfn|Williams|Queen|1999|p=118}}
==Dharma heirs== Matsuoka named many [[Dharma heir]]s, though their qualifications as teachers have been questioned, given the short time of practice required by Matsuoka and the absence of formal ordination.{{sfn|Ford|2006|p=80–81}} According to Kozen Sampson, at least three of Matsuoka's students received inka shomei. These three "were considered to be fully transmitted priests with the status of Roshi by him".<ref name=Samson /> Four students were registered with the Soto-Shu as "initial novice priest", and to five students was conferred "full priesthood".<ref name=Samson>[https://mtadamszen.org/dedication-to-soyu-matsuoka-zenkaku-roshi/ Mount Adams Zen Center, ''Rev. Dr. Soyu Zengaku Matsuoka, Roshi. 25 November 1912 – 20 November 1997'']</ref>
There are four living Dharma Heirs of Soyu Matsuoka: * Hogaku Shozen McGuire, * Zenkai Taiun Michael Elliston, * Kaiten Johndennis Govert, * Shogaku Zenshin Stephen Echard Musgrave, who retired from the Zen institute of San Diego due to ill health.
Hogaku established Daibutsuji Zen Temple in Cloudcroft and the [[Zen Center of Las Cruces]], in Las Cruces, New Mexico. So Gozen is now the Abbot of Daibutsuji and the Zen Center of Las Cruces.<ref>[http://www.nmprc.state.nm.us/cgi-bin/prcdtl.cgi?1372796+DAIBUTSUJI+ZEN+TEMPLE NMPRC.state.nm.us]</ref> Daiho Hilbert left Daibutsuji to establish the [[Order of Clear Mind Zen]], a socially engaged sangha in New Mexico.<ref>[http://www.nmprc.state.nm.us/cgi-bin/prcdtl.cgi?4313136+ORDER+OF+CLEAR+MIND+ZEN NMPRC.state.nm.us]</ref> Taiun Elliston Sensei established the Atlanta Soto Zen Center and is working to establish an order honoring Matsuoka.
