'''Ted Cohen''' (1939 - March 14, 2014) was an American philosopher and professor of [[philosophy]] at [[University of Chicago]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ted Cohen, 1939-2014 |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-ted-cohen-obituary-met-20140330-story.html |accessdate=23 June 2018 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ted Cohen (1939-2014) - Daily Nous |url=http://dailynous.com/2014/03/17/ted-cohen/ |website=[[Daily Nous]] |accessdate=23 June 2018}}</ref> His interests included philosophy of art, history of the philosophy of art, especially in the 18th-century, and the philosophy of language.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://philosophy.uchicago.edu/faculty/cohen.html|title=Ted Cohen {{!}} The Department of Philosophy {{!}} The University of Chicago Division of the Humanities|website=philosophy.uchicago.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-07-23}}</ref>
== Education and career== Cohen received his Bachelor of Arts (BA) from the University of Chicago in 1962, a Masters in Arts (MA) from Harvard in 1965 and a PhD from Harvard in 1972 (Titled: The grammar of taste). He taught at the University of Chicago from 1967. Cohen worked mainly in the philosophy of art.<ref name=":0" />
Cohen served as president of the [[American Philosophical Association]] (2006-2007) and the [[American Society for Aesthetics]] (1997-1998).<ref>{{cite news |title=Ted Cohen, philosopher who found the extraordinary in the ordinary, 1939-2014 |url=https://news.uchicago.edu/story/ted-cohen-philosopher-who-found-extraordinary-ordinary-1939-2014 |accessdate=23 June 2018 |work=[[University of Chicago News]] |language=en}}</ref>
He was also the moderator of the [[Latke–Hamantash Debate]] at the University of Chicago for 25 years until his death.
==Selected books== *''Essays in Kant's Aesthetics'', edited with [[Paul Guyer]] (University of Chicago Press, 1982) *''Jokes: Philosophical Thoughts on Joking Matters'' (University of Chicago Press, 1999). *''Thinking of Others: On the Talent for Metaphor'' (Princeton University Press, 2008). *''Serious Larks: The Philosophy of Ted Cohen'', edited edited and introduced by Daniel Herwitz. (University of Chicago Press, 2018)
